    <item>
      <title>Twin Reports Indicate Oceans May Rise Higher &amp; Much Faster</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/oconline.github.io/insights/2014/2014-12-05_entry369/</link>
      <pubDate>Fri, 05 Dec 2014 18:09:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/oconline.github.io/insights/2014/2014-12-05_entry369/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&#34;&#34; width=&#34;303&#34; height=&#34;263&#34; align=&#34;right&#34; style=&#34;margin: 0px 0px 5px 5px; float: right; display: inline;&#34; src=&#34;http://www.nasa.gov/sites/default/files/antarctica_amundsen_sea_sector-1.jpg&#34;&gt;&lt;/img&gt;Two joint studies are out this week and indicate that the United Nations&amp;rsquo; Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) 2013&amp;rsquo;s predictions of a global sea rise of a bit over 3 feet by the end of the century could be way off.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>North America facing &#39;megadrought&#39;?</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/oconline.github.io/insights/2012/2012-08-02_entry289/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 02 Aug 2012 17:48:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/oconline.github.io/insights/2012/2012-08-02_entry289/</guid>
      <description>&lt;div class=&#34;wlWriterHeaderFooter&#34; style=&#34;padding-bottom: 4px; margin: 0px; padding-left: 0px; padding-right: 0px; float: none; padding-top: 4px;&#34;&gt;&lt;iframe src=&#34;http://www.facebook.com/widgets/like.php?href=http://vashonbeprepared.org/News/Blogs/VashonPreparedness/tabid/164/EntryId/289/North-America-facing-megadrought.aspx&#34; frameborder=&#34;0&#34; scrolling=&#34;no&#34; style=&#34;width: 130px; height: 80px;border: medium none;&#34;&gt;&lt;/iframe&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;img width=&#34;431&#34; height=&#34;256&#34; title=&#34;Figure 4: Drought over western North America from 800 to 2100. Reconstructed summer PDSI from 800 to 2006, five-year mean. Black rectangles show Stine no. 1 and Stine no. 2 megadroughts. Red circles denote five-year drought events as severe as the turn of the century event. Red line denotes the mean PDSI &#34; align=&#34;right&#34; style=&#34;margin: 0px 0px 5px 5px; display: inline; float: right;&#34; alt=&#34;Drought over western North America from 800 to 2100.&#34; src=&#34;http://www.nature.com/ngeo/journal/v5/n8/carousel/ngeo1529-f4.jpg&#34; /&gt;Western North America experienced the strongest drought in 800 years from 2000 to 2004 &amp;ndash; but that may be the new normal for the next century. &lt;em&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://www.nature.com/ngeo/journal/v5/n8/pdf/ngeo1529.pdf&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;Reduction in carbon uptake during turn of the century drought in western North America &amp;ndash; pg 551 &amp;ndash; 556&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/em&gt;, by a group of 10 researchers in the &lt;a href=&#34;http://www.nature.com/ngeo/journal/v5/n8/index.html&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;current issue of Nature Geoscience&lt;/a&gt;, looks at the reduced carbon uptake (by 51%) in drought stressed forests, based on a study of the 2000-2004 drought throughout western North America.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Global Warming Moves us Closer to the Ultimate Disaster</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/oconline.github.io/insights/2012/2012-01-11_entry215/</link>
      <pubDate>Wed, 11 Jan 2012 21:34:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/oconline.github.io/insights/2012/2012-01-11_entry215/</guid>
      <description>&lt;div class=&#34;wlWriterHeaderFooter&#34; style=&#34;padding-bottom: 4px; margin: 0px; padding-left: 0px; padding-right: 0px; float: none; padding-top: 4px;&#34;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&lt;h4&gt;Doomsday clock moves closer to midnight&lt;/h4&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://www.thebulletin.org/content/doomsday-clock/overview&#34;&gt;&lt;img align=&#34;right&#34; style=&#34;margin: 0px 0px 5px 5px; display: inline; float: right;&#34; alt=&#34;The Doomsday Clock&#34; src=&#34;http://www.thebulletin.org/sites/all/themes/bas/images/clock.png?5&#34; /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Numerous articles (including &lt;a href=&#34;http://content.usatoday.com/communities/sciencefair/post/2012/01/doomsday-clock-atomic-scientists-nuclear-war-energy/1?loc=interstitialskip&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;USA Today&amp;rsquo;s&lt;/a&gt;) note that &lt;a href=&#34;http://www.thebulletin.org/&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;scientists&lt;/a&gt; have moved the hands of the &lt;a href=&#34;http://www.thebulletin.org/content/doomsday-clock/overview&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;doomsday clock&lt;/a&gt; toward midnight &amp;ndash; as a visible metaphor for our lessened security due to &lt;a href=&#34;http://bos.sagepub.com/content/68/1/39.full&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;our fuelish ways&lt;/a&gt;.&amp;nbsp; It is notoriously hard to change our social (i.e., automotive) ways, but the consequences of our not taking a long term view are increasingly resulting in massive storm and economic damage today to societies across the globe. &lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Cost of Global Warming Apparent as US Reaches 12th Mega-Disasters in 2011-- each over a Billion $</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/oconline.github.io/insights/2011/2011-12-08_entry208/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 08 Dec 2011 16:43:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/oconline.github.io/insights/2011/2011-12-08_entry208/</guid>
      <description>&lt;div class=&#34;wlWriterHeaderFooter&#34; style=&#34;padding-bottom: 4px; margin: 0px; padding-left: 0px; padding-right: 0px; float: none; padding-top: 4px;&#34;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;./images/208/Windows-Live-Writer-5bf7f0a7ff0a_70D8-image_2.png&#34;&gt;&lt;img title=&#34;image&#34; style=&#34;background-image: none;   margin: 0px 0px 5px 5px; padding-left: 0px; padding-right: 0px; display: inline; float: right;   padding-top: 0px;border: 0px solid;&#34; alt=&#34;Graphic from IPCC&#39;s &#34; src=&#34;./images/208/Windows-Live-Writer-5bf7f0a7ff0a_70D8-image_thumb.png&#34; /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-201_162-57339130/2011-deals-u.s-12-billion-dollar-disasters&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;CBS&lt;/a&gt; notes that this year&amp;rsquo;s 12 disasters costing over 1 billion dollars each surpasses the number seen during all the 1980&amp;rsquo;s &amp;ndash; even with inflation adjustments. In associated &lt;a href=&#34;http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-205_162-57327472/climate-scientists-more-extreme-weather-coming&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;reports&lt;/a&gt; they note that the &lt;a href=&#34;http://www.ipcc.ch/news_and_events/docs/ipcc34/SREX_FD_SPM_final.pdf&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change&amp;rsquo;s&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=&#34;http://www.eenews.net/public/climatewire/2011/11/18/1?page_type=print&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;latest report&lt;/a&gt; indicated that additional small and large disasters can be expected with global warming.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
